Setup Question	= Intel(R) Turbo Boost Technology
Help String	= Turbo Boost automatically allows individual CPU cores to run faster than stock frequency if the processor is operating within power, temperature and current limitations. This can improve performance in single-threaded applications.  Enable =  Turbo Boost will operate at stock settings  Auto = Turbo Boost will operate at stock settings, except when the base clock frequency is altered  Disable = Disables  Turbo Boost. All CPU cores will operate at settings specified by the CPU clock ratio (above). Recommended setting for overclocking.

// FORM
// FORM ID	= 2795
// Title	= Intel ICC

// GUID	= ec87d643-eba4-4bb5-a1e5-3f3e36b20da9
// Variable	= Setup
Setup Question	= ICC/OC Watchdog Timer
Help String	= When enabled, the ICC/OC watchdog timer is exposed to OS as an ACPI device. WDT HW is always used by BIOS when clock settings are changed.
Token	=4B4	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=3AD
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]Disabled 
Options	=*[00]Disabled	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]Enabled

// GUID	= 64192dca-d034-49d2-a6de-65a829eb4c74
// Variable	= IccAdvancedSetupDataVar
Setup Question	= ICC Locks after EOP
Help String	= Specifies the ICC registers that can be written after end-of-post. Default - Dynamic registers for runtime clock adjustments are left writeable. All Locked - No clock register adjustments allowed after EOP. All Unlocked - All ICC registers can be written after EOP.
Token	=2796	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=0E
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]Default 
Options	=*[00]Default	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]All Locked
         [02]All Unlocked

// GUID	= 64192dca-d034-49d2-a6de-65a829eb4c74
// Variable	= IccAdvancedSetupDataVar
Setup Question	= ICC Profile
Help String	= Select clock profile that corresponds to the platform configuration. Profiles are defined by the OEM and platform capabilites. Tpically, profile 0 has failsafe settings. Other profiles correspond to WiMax, 3G, or Overclocking settings.
Token	=2797	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=0D
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=<0> 
Value	=<0>

// SUBTITLE	= DMI/BCLK Clock Settings

// GUID	= 64192dca-d034-49d2-a6de-65a829eb4c74
// Variable	= IccAdvancedSetupDataVar
Setup Question	=     Clock Frequency
Help String	= Specifies new frequency to be applied. Frequency is rounded to nearest valid value. Allowed range is limited by the Max/Min supported frequencies. Changes are not applied until settings are saved and platform resets.
Token	=2798	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=02
Width	=02
BIOS Default	=<0> 
Value	=<10000>

// GUID	= 64192dca-d034-49d2-a6de-65a829eb4c74
// Variable	= IccAdvancedSetupDataVar
Setup Question	=     Spread %
Help String	= Specifies the amount of spread spectrum clocking to be applied to the base clock frequency in 0.01% increments. Allowed range is limited by Maximum Spread % and supported Spread mode Adjustements. If Changes Allowed, a value between 0 and Max Spread % can be specified. Value is adjusted to settings supported by HW. If only Halt Allowed, only 0% and default spread % can be specified. Changes are not applied until settings are saved and platform resets.
Token	=2799	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=05
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=<0> 
Value	=<0>

// SUBTITLE	= Uncore

// GUID	= ec87d643-eba4-4bb5-a1e5-3f3e36b20da9
// Variable	= Setup
Setup Question	= Uncore Voltage Offset
Help String	= Specifies the Offset Voltage applied to the Uncore domain. This voltage is specified in millivolts. Uses Mailbox MSR 0x150, cmd 0x11. Range -1000 to 1000 mV
Token	=4F1	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=8D7
Width	=02
BIOS Default	=<0> 
Value	=<0>

// GUID	= ec87d643-eba4-4bb5-a1e5-3f3e36b20da9
// Variable	= Setup
Setup Question	=   Offset Prefix
Help String	= Sets the offset value as positive or negative.
Token	=4F2	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=8D9
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]+ 
Options	=*[00]+	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]-

// FORM
// FORM ID	= 271A
// Title	= Security

// SUBTITLE	= Password Description

// SUBTITLE	= If ONLY the Administrator's password is set,

// SUBTITLE	= then this only limits access to Setup and is

// SUBTITLE	= only asked for when entering Setup.

// SUBTITLE	= If ONLY the User's password is set, then this

// SUBTITLE	= is a power on password and must be entered to

// SUBTITLE	= boot or enter Setup. In Setup the User will

// SUBTITLE	= have Administrator rights.

// SUBTITLE	= The password length must be

// SUBTITLE	= in the following range:

// FORM
// FORM ID	= 271B
// Title	= Power Management

// GUID	= ec87d643-eba4-4bb5-a1e5-3f3e36b20da9
// Variable	= Setup
// Setup Question	= AC BACK
// Help String	= Determine the state of  the system after the power returns after AC power loss.  Always Off = System stays off upon power return  Always On = System is turned on up power return  Memory = System returns to last know awake state upon power return
// Token	=DCA	// Do NOT change this line
// Offset	=43E
// Width	=01
// BIOS Default	=[02]Always Off 
// Options	=[00]Memory	// Move "*" to the desired Option
//         [01]Always On
//         *[02]Always Off

// GUID	= ec87d643-eba4-4bb5-a1e5-3f3e36b20da9
// Variable	= Setup
// Setup Question	= Power On By Keyboard
// Help String	= Enable or disable the system to wake from C-state via keyboard (PS2 only)  Disabled = function disabled  Any Key = Press any key to turn on system  Keyboard 98 = Press power on Windows 98 keyboard  to turn on system  Password = Set a password (1-5 characters) to turn on system
// Token	=DCB	// Do NOT change this line
// Offset	=43F
// Width	=01
// BIOS Default	=[00]Disabled 
// Options	=*[00]Disabled	// Move "*" to the desired Option
//         [01]Password
//         [02]Keyboard 98
//         [03]Any key

// GUID	= ec87d643-eba4-4bb5-a1e5-3f3e36b20da9
// Variable	= Setup
// Setup Question	= Power On By Mouse
// Help String	= Enables the system to wake up via PS2 mouse.  Disabled = Function is disabled  Move = Move the mouse to turn on system  Double Click = Double click left button on mouse to turn on system
// Token	=DCD	// Do NOT change this line
// Offset	=441
// Width	=01
// BIOS Default	=[00]Disabled 
// Options	=*[00]Disabled	// Move "*" to the desired Option

//         [02]Double Click

// GUID	= ec87d643-eba4-4bb5-a1e5-3f3e36b20da9
// Variable	= Setup
// Setup Question	= ErP
// Help String	= Configure the ErP Mode configuration.
// Token	=DCE	// Do NOT change this line
// Offset	=444
// Width	=01
// BIOS Default	=[00]Disabled 
// Options	=*[00]Disabled	// Move "*" to the desired Option
//         [01]Enabled

// GUID	= ec87d643-eba4-4bb5-a1e5-3f3e36b20da9
// Variable	= Setup
Setup Question	= Soft-Off by PWR-BTTN
Help String	= Configure the way to turn off the computer in MS-DOS mode via the power button.  Instant Off = System will be turned off instantly using the power button.  Delay 4 seconds = User must press and hold the power button for 4 seconds to turn off the system. If pressed for less than 4 seconds, it will enter suspend mode.
Token	=DCF	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=445
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]Instant-Off 
Options	=*[00]Instant-Off	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]Delay 4 Sec.

Setup Question	= Power Loading
Help String	= Enables or Disables dummy load.When the power supply is at low load, a self-protection will activate causing it to shutdown or fail.If this occurs, please set to Enabled.
Token	=DD0	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=446
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]Auto 
Options	=*[00]Auto	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]Disabled
         [02]Enabled
